<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-01-21T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-01-21T09:00:00-05:00" n="853" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d853">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">833.5151/462: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Uruguay</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Reed</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Montevideo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-01-21T11:00:00-03:00">January 21, 1938—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received January 21—9:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>8. Import quotas of 11 countries have been increased by 50 per cent and
                            British by 250 per cent but United States still excluded. Exchange
                            Control says value of American merchandise blocked in Montevideo
                            customhouse without quota is 1½ million dollars.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Reed</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>